A quarter fell from the man's hand and landed standing up on a slice of pizza. One of the workers just took the quarter off, but didn't get rid of the slice, and just kept serving as if it didn't happen. The DeKalb Avenue Two Bros Pizzeria is certainly a well cherished and important eatery within the downtown Flatbush Avenue region.  In comparison to other $1 per slice pizzerias, Two Bros DeKalb Avenue location offers ample seating space, but I strongly discourage those patronizing the establishment from sitting down and enjoying their $1 slice of pizza due to the vast numbers of boisterous Long Island University students, Brooklyn Technical High School pupils and the occasional unsightly pan-handlers who may wonder into the pizzeria; it is best to purchase your pizza and then go enjoy your meal in a more alluring atmosphere.  In regards to the taste and size of the pizza slices, Two Bros DeKalb Avenue location is by far among the very best; the one $1 slice is served fresh and hot.  In addition, Two Bros  DeKalb Avenue does offer a vast variety of gourmet slices, from the barbecue chicken pizza to the population pepperoni with extra cheese.  Two Bros DeKalb Avenue pizzeria has inadvertently brought down the aggregate prices of all the neighbouring eateries by offering a $1 option to the far more expensive fast food meal combinations and the $5 hero sandwiches.  This is an extremely no frills eatery that has serves the neighborhood extremely well.  I strongly recommend and support their businesses model, profit through sales volume.👏🏿

When it comes to pizza, I judge base on two criteria.  Taste and price.  2 Bros is an open store franchise with many locations across the 5 Boroughs.  The decor is simple, clean, and really just simple. There are low tables with seats and a long strip bench that's against the wall. It is very spacious, but often enough you'll find yourself looking at a long line of customers.  Reason for this is the pizza. While I mention this. Note that the plain pizza slice is only a dollar. The toppings pizza cost extra, I believe only 50 cent extra. It's quite cheap and affordable if you're on a tight budget, which is perfect for those who are college students *ahem L.I.U.*.  Now taste, if you want to have if a place has quality pizza, always try a plain slice. In my honest opinion, the pizza was not gray, and it's not bad. If I was hungry, this is what I would eat. If I was on a tight budget, this is what I would eat. If I had some money to spare and I wasn't all that hungry, I would go elsewhere.  Again, I reiterate, nice atmosphere, cheap affordable pizza, and really wallet friendly. But if you're a person who judges the taste more than the price, stay away.  As far as I know, they only serve pizza, so don't go looking for garlic knots or calzones.
